UnavailableFeature.name: UnavailableFeature
UnavailableFeature.doc:
int([x]) -> integer
int(x, base=10) -> integer

Convert a number or string to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments
are given.  If x is a number, return x.__int__().  For floating point
numbers, this truncates towards zero.

If x is not a number or if base is given, then x must be a string,
bytes, or bytearray instance representing an integer literal in the
given base.  The literal can be preceded by '+' or '-' and be surrounded
by whitespace.  The base defaults to 10.  Valid bases are 0 and 2-36.
Base 0 means to interpret the base from the string as an integer literal.
>>> int('0b100', base=0)
4

bit_length.name: bit_length
bit_length.doc:
Number of bits necessary to represent self in binary.

>>> bin(37)
'0b100101'
>>> (37).bit_length()
6

conjugate.name: conjugate
conjugate.doc: Returns self, the complex conjugate of any int.

from_bytes.name: from_bytes
from_bytes.doc:
Return the integer represented by the given array of bytes.

bytes
  Holds the array of bytes to convert.  The argument must either
  support the buffer protocol or be an iterable object producing bytes.
  Bytes and bytearray are examples of built-in objects that support the
  buffer protocol.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Indicates whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.

to_bytes.name: to_bytes
to_bytes.doc:
Return an array of bytes representing an integer.

length
  Length of bytes object to use.  An OverflowError is raised if the
  integer is not representable with the given number of bytes.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Determines whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.
  If signed is False and a negative integer is given, an OverflowError
  is raised.

FilterType.name: FilterType
FilterType.doc:
int([x]) -> integer
int(x, base=10) -> integer

Convert a number or string to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments
are given.  If x is a number, return x.__int__().  For floating point
numbers, this truncates towards zero.

If x is not a number or if base is given, then x must be a string,
bytes, or bytearray instance representing an integer literal in the
given base.  The literal can be preceded by '+' or '-' and be surrounded
by whitespace.  The base defaults to 10.  Valid bases are 0 and 2-36.
Base 0 means to interpret the base from the string as an integer literal.
>>> int('0b100', base=0)
4

bit_length.name: bit_length
bit_length.doc:
Number of bits necessary to represent self in binary.

>>> bin(37)
'0b100101'
>>> (37).bit_length()
6

conjugate.name: conjugate
conjugate.doc: Returns self, the complex conjugate of any int.

from_bytes.name: from_bytes
from_bytes.doc:
Return the integer represented by the given array of bytes.

bytes
  Holds the array of bytes to convert.  The argument must either
  support the buffer protocol or be an iterable object producing bytes.
  Bytes and bytearray are examples of built-in objects that support the
  buffer protocol.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Indicates whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.

to_bytes.name: to_bytes
to_bytes.doc:
Return an array of bytes representing an integer.

length
  Length of bytes object to use.  An OverflowError is raised if the
  integer is not representable with the given number of bytes.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Determines whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.
  If signed is False and a negative integer is given, an OverflowError
  is raised.

denominator.name: denominator
denominator.doc: the denominator of a rational number in lowest terms

imag.name: imag
imag.doc: the imaginary part of a complex number

numerator.name: numerator
numerator.doc: the numerator of a rational number in lowest terms

real.name: real
real.doc: the real part of a complex number

devices.doc: Return const access to all available Devices that are present in the chains

has_audio_input.name: has_audio_input
has_audio_input.doc:
return True, if this Chain can be feed with an Audio signal. This is
true for all Audio Chains.

has_audio_output.name: has_audio_output
has_audio_output.doc:
return True, if this Chain sends out an Audio signal. This is
true for all Audio Chains, and MIDI chains with an Instrument.

has_midi_input.name: has_midi_input
has_midi_input.doc:
return True, if this Chain can be feed with an Audio signal. This is
true for all MIDI Chains.

has_midi_output.name: has_midi_output
has_midi_output.doc:
return True, if this Chain sends out MIDI events. This is
true for all MIDI Chains with no Instruments.

is_auto_colored.name: is_auto_colored
is_auto_colored.doc:
Get/set access to the auto color flag of the Chain.
If True, the Chain will always have the same color as the containing
Track or Chain.

mixer_device.name: mixer_device
mixer_device.doc:
Return access to the mixer device that holds the chain's mixer parameters:
the Volume, Pan, and Sendamounts.

muted_via_solo.name: muted_via_solo
muted_via_solo.doc:
Return const access to whether this chain is muted due to some other chain
being soloed.

name.name: name
name.doc: Read/write access to the name of the Chain, as visible in the track header.

solo.name: solo
solo.doc:
Get/Set the solo status of the chain. Note that this will not disable the
solo state of any other Chain in the same rack. If you want exclusive solo, 
you have to disable the solo state of the other Chains manually.

ChainMixerDevice.name: ChainMixerDevice

access to the Volume, Panning, and Send properties of a Chain.

apply_note_modifications.name: apply_note_modifications
apply_note_modifications.doc:
apply_note_modifications( (Clip)arg1, (MidiNoteVector)arg2) -> None :
    Expects a list of notes as returned from get_notes_extended. The content
    of the list will be used to modify existing notes in the clip, based on
    matching note IDs.
    This function should be used when modifying existing notes, e.g. changing the
    velocity or start time. The function ensures that per-note events attached to
    the modified notes are preserved. This is NOT the case when replacing notes
    via a combination of remove_notes_extended and add_new_notes.
    The given list can be a subset of the notes in the clip, but it must not
    contain any notes that are not present in the clip.
    

    C++ signature :
        void apply_note_modifications(TPyHandle<AClip>,std::__1::vector<NClipApi::TNoteInfo, std::__1::allocator<NClipApi::TNoteInfo>>)

    If not looped, the region outside the start and end markers is removed.

duplicate_notes_by_id.name: duplicate_notes_by_id
duplicate_notes_by_id.doc:
duplicate_notes_by_id( (Clip)self, (object)note_ids [, (object)destination_time=None [, (int)transposition_amount=0]]) -> IntU64Vector :
    Duplicate all notes matching the given note IDs.
    If the optional destination_time is not provided, new notes will be inserted
    after the last selected note. This behavior can be observed when duplicating
    notes in the Live GUI.
    If the transposition_amount is specified, the notes in the region will be
    transposed by the number of semitones.
    Raises an error on audio clips.

    C++ signature :
        std::__1::vector<unsigned long long, std::__1::allocator<unsigned long long>> duplicate_notes_by_id(TPyHandle<AClip>,boost::python::api::object [,boost::python::api::object=None [,int=0]])

    Duplicate the notes in the specified region to the destination_time.
    Only notes of the specified pitch are duplicated or all if pitch is -1.
    If the transposition_amount is not 0, the notes in the region will
    be transposed by the transpose_amount of semitones.Raises an error on audio clips.

    C++ signature :
        void duplicate_region(TPyHandle<AClip>,double,double,double [,int=-1 [,int=0]])

available_warp_modes.name: available_warp_modes
available_warp_modes.doc:
Available for AudioClips only.
Get/Set the available warp modes, that can be used.

canonical_parent.name: canonical_parent
canonical_parent.doc: Get the canonical parent of the Clip.

color.name: color
color.doc: Get/set access to the color of the Clip (RGB).

color_index.name: color_index
color_index.doc: Get/set access to the color index of the Clip.

end_marker.name: end_marker
end_marker.doc: Get/Set the Clips end marker pos in beats/seconds (unit depends on warping).

file_path.name: file_path
file_path.doc: Get the path of the file represented by the Audio Clip.

gain.name: gain
gain.doc:
Available for AudioClips only.
Read/write access to the gain setting of the
Audio Clip

gain_display_string.name: gain_display_string
gain_display_string.doc: Return a string with the gain as dB value

groove.name: groove
groove.doc: Get the groove associated with this clip.

has_envelopes.name: has_envelopes
has_envelopes.doc: Will notify if the clip gets his first envelope or the last envelope is removed.

has_groove.name: has_groove
has_groove.doc: Returns true if a groove is associated with this clip.

is_arrangement_clip.name: is_arrangement_clip
is_arrangement_clip.doc:
return true if this Clip is an Arrangement Clip.
A Clip can be either a Session or Arrangement Clip.

is_audio_clip.name: is_audio_clip
is_audio_clip.doc:
Return true if this Clip is an Audio Clip.
A Clip can be either an Audioclip or a MIDI Clip.

is_midi_clip.name: is_midi_clip
is_midi_clip.doc:
return true if this Clip is a MIDI Clip.
A Clip can be either an Audioclip or a MIDI Clip.

is_overdubbing.name: is_overdubbing
is_overdubbing.doc: returns true if the Clip is recording overdubs

is_playing.name: is_playing
is_playing.doc:
Get/Set if this Clip is currently playing. If the Clips trigger mode
is set to a quantization value, the Clip will not start playing immediately.
If you need to know wether the Clip was triggered, use the is_triggered property.

is_recording.name: is_recording
is_recording.doc: returns true if the Clip was triggered to record or is recording.

is_triggered.name: is_triggered
is_triggered.doc: returns true if the Clip was triggered or is playing.

launch_mode.name: launch_mode
launch_mode.doc: Get/Set access to the launch mode setting of the Clip.

launch_quantization.name: launch_quantization
launch_quantization.doc: Get/Set access to the launch quantization setting of the Clip.

legato.name: legato
legato.doc: Get/Set access to the legato setting of the Clip

length.name: length
length.doc: Get to the Clips length in beats/seconds (unit depends on warping).

loop_end.name: loop_end
loop_end.doc: Get/Set the loop end pos of this Clip in beats/seconds (unit depends on warping).

loop_start.name: loop_start
loop_start.doc: Get/Set the Clips loopstart pos in beats/seconds (unit depends on warping).

looping.name: looping
looping.doc:
Get/Set the Clips 'loop is enabled' flag
.Only Warped Audio Clips or MIDI Clip can be looped.

muted.name: muted
muted.doc: Read/write access to the mute state of the Clip.

name.name: name
name.doc: Read/write access to the name of the Clip.

pitch_coarse.name: pitch_coarse
pitch_coarse.doc:
Available for AudioClips only.
Read/write access to the pitch (in halftones) setting of the
Audio Clip, ranging from -48 to 48

pitch_fine.name: pitch_fine
pitch_fine.doc:
Available for AudioClips only.
Read/write access to the pitch fine setting of the
Audio Clip, ranging from -500 to 500

playing_position.name: playing_position
playing_position.doc:
Constant access to the current playing position of the clip.
The returned value is the position in beats for midi and warped audio clips,
or in seconds for unwarped audio clips. Stopped clips will return 0.

position.name: position
position.doc: Get/Set the loop position of this Clip in beats/seconds (unit depends on warping).

ram_mode.name: ram_mode
ram_mode.doc:
Available for AudioClips only.
Read/write access to the Ram mode setting of the Audio Clip

sample_length.name: sample_length
sample_length.doc:
Available for AudioClips only.
Get the sample length in sample time or -1 if there is no sample available.

sample_rate.name: sample_rate
sample_rate.doc:
Available for AudioClips only.
Read-only access to the Clip's sampling rate.

signature_denominator.name: signature_denominator
signature_denominator.doc: Get/Set access to the global signature denominator of the Clip.

signature_numerator.name: signature_numerator
signature_numerator.doc: Get/Set access to the global signature numerator of the Clip.

start_marker.name: start_marker
start_marker.doc: Get/Set the Clips start marker pos in beats/seconds (unit depends on warping).

start_time.name: start_time
start_time.doc: Get the clip's start time offset. For Session View clips, this is the time the clip was started. For Arrangement View clips, this is the offset within the arrangement.

velocity_amount.name: velocity_amount
velocity_amount.doc: Get/Set access to the velocity to volume amount of the Clip.

view.name: view
view.doc: Get the view of the Clip.

warp_markers.name: warp_markers
warp_markers.doc:
Available for AudioClips only.
Get the warp markers for this audio clip.

warp_mode.name: warp_mode
warp_mode.doc:
Available for AudioClips only.
Get/Set the warp mode for this audio clip.

warping.name: warping
warping.doc:
Available for AudioClips only.
Get/Set if this Clip is timestreched.

will_record_on_start.name: will_record_on_start
will_record_on_start.doc: returns true if the Clip will record on being started.

ClipLaunchQuantization.name: ClipLaunchQuantization
ClipLaunchQuantization.doc:
int([x]) -> integer
int(x, base=10) -> integer

Convert a number or string to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments
are given.  If x is a number, return x.__int__().  For floating point
numbers, this truncates towards zero.

If x is not a number or if base is given, then x must be a string,
bytes, or bytearray instance representing an integer literal in the
given base.  The literal can be preceded by '+' or '-' and be surrounded
by whitespace.  The base defaults to 10.  Valid bases are 0 and 2-36.

    Duplicates the slot's clip to the passed in target slot.
    Overrides the target's clip if it's not empty.
    Raises an exception if the (source) slot itself is empty, or if source and
    target have different track types (audio vs. MIDI). Also raises if the source
    or target slot is in a group track (so called group slot).

    C++ signature :
        void duplicate_clip_to(TPyHandle<AGroupAndClipSlotBase>,TPyHandle<AGroupAndClipSlotBase>)

fire.name: fire
fire.doc:
fire( (ClipSlot)arg1) -> None :
    Fire a Clip if this Clipslot owns one, else trigger the stop button,
    if we have one.

    C++ signature :
        void fire(TPyHandle<AGroupAndClipSlotBase>)

fire( (ClipSlot)self [, (float)record_length=1.7976931348623157e+308 [, (int)launch_quantization=-2147483648 [, (bool)force_legato=False]]]) -> None :
    If 'record_length' is passed, the clip will be refired after the given recording length.  Raises an error if the slot owns a clip.
    'launch_quantization' determines the quantization of global transport that is applied overriding the value in the song.
    'force_legato' will make the clip play inmediatelly. The playhead will be moved to keep the clip synchronized.

    C++ signature :
        void fire(TPyHandle<AGroupAndClipSlotBase> [,double=1.7976931348623157e+308 [,int=-2147483648 [,bool=False]]])

AudioToMidiType.name: AudioToMidiType
AudioToMidiType.doc:
int([x]) -> integer
int(x, base=10) -> integer

Convert a number or string to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments
are given.  If x is a number, return x.__int__().  For floating point
numbers, this truncates towards zero.

If x is not a number or if base is given, then x must be a string,
bytes, or bytearray instance representing an integer literal in the
given base.  The literal can be preceded by '+' or '-' and be surrounded
by whitespace.  The base defaults to 10.  Valid bases are 0 and 2-36.
Base 0 means to interpret the base from the string as an integer literal.
>>> int('0b100', base=0)
4

from_bytes.name: from_bytes
from_bytes.doc:
Return the integer represented by the given array of bytes.

bytes
  Holds the array of bytes to convert.  The argument must either
  support the buffer protocol or be an iterable object producing bytes.
  Bytes and bytearray are examples of built-in objects that support the
  buffer protocol.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Indicates whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.

to_bytes.name: to_bytes
to_bytes.doc:
Return an array of bytes representing an integer.

length
  Length of bytes object to use.  An OverflowError is raised if the
  integer is not representable with the given number of bytes.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Determines whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.
  If signed is False and a negative integer is given, an OverflowError
  is raised.

AutomationState.name: AutomationState
AutomationState.doc:
int([x]) -> integer
int(x, base=10) -> integer

Convert a number or string to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments
are given.  If x is a number, return x.__int__().  For floating point
numbers, this truncates towards zero.

If x is not a number or if base is given, then x must be a string,
bytes, or bytearray instance representing an integer literal in the
given base.  The literal can be preceded by '+' or '-' and be surrounded
by whitespace.  The base defaults to 10.  Valid bases are 0 and 2-36.
Base 0 means to interpret the base from the string as an integer literal.
>>> int('0b100', base=0)
4

bit_length.name: bit_length
bit_length.doc:
Number of bits necessary to represent self in binary.

>>> bin(37)
'0b100101'
>>> (37).bit_length()
6

conjugate.name: conjugate
conjugate.doc: Returns self, the complex conjugate of any int.

from_bytes.name: from_bytes
from_bytes.doc:
Return the integer represented by the given array of bytes.

bytes
  Holds the array of bytes to convert.  The argument must either
  support the buffer protocol or be an iterable object producing bytes.
  Bytes and bytearray are examples of built-in objects that support the
  buffer protocol.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Indicates whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.

to_bytes.name: to_bytes
to_bytes.doc:
Return an array of bytes representing an integer.

length
  Length of bytes object to use.  An OverflowError is raised if the
  integer is not representable with the given number of bytes.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Determines whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.
  If signed is False and a negative integer is given, an OverflowError
  is raised.

default_value.name: default_value
default_value.doc:
Return the default value for this parameter.  A Default value is only
available for non-quantized parameter types (see 'is_quantized').

is_enabled.name: is_enabled
is_enabled.doc: Returns false if the parameter has been macro mapped or disabled by Max.

is_quantized.name: is_quantized
is_quantized.doc:
Returns True, if this value is a boolean or integer like switch.
Non quantized values are continues float values.

max.name: max
max.doc:
Returns const access to the upper value of the allowed range for
this parameter

min.name: min
min.doc:
Returns const access to the lower value of the allowed range for
this parameter

name.name: name
name.doc:
Returns const access the name of this parameter, as visible in Lives
automation choosers.

original_name.name: original_name
original_name.doc:
Returns const access the original name of this parameter, unaffected of
any renamings.

short_value_items.name: short_value_items
short_value_items.doc: Return the list of possible values for this parameter. Like value_items, but prefers short value names if available. Raises an error if 'is_quantized' is False.

state.name: state
state.doc:
Returns the state of the parameter:
- enabled - the parameter's value can be changed,
- irrelevant - the parameter is enabled, but value changes will not take any effect until it gets enabled,
- disabled - the parameter's value cannot be changed.

value.name: value
value.doc:
Get/Set the current value (as visible in the GUI) this parameter.
The value must be inside the min/max properties of this device.

value_items.name: value_items
value_items.doc: Return the list of possible values for this parameter. Raises an error if 'is_quantized' is False.

EditMode.name: EditMode
EditMode.doc:
int([x]) -> integer
int(x, base=10) -> integer

Convert a number or string to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments
are given.  If x is a number, return x.__int__().  For floating point
numbers, this truncates towards zero.

If x is not a number or if base is given, then x must be a string,
bytes, or bytearray instance representing an integer literal in the
given base.  The literal can be preceded by '+' or '-' and be surrounded
by whitespace.  The base defaults to 10.  Valid bases are 0 and 2-36.
Base 0 means to interpret the base from the string as an integer literal.
>>> int('0b100', base=0)
4

bit_length.name: bit_length
bit_length.doc:
Number of bits necessary to represent self in binary.

>>> bin(37)
'0b100101'
>>> (37).bit_length()
6

conjugate.name: conjugate
conjugate.doc: Returns self, the complex conjugate of any int.

from_bytes.name: from_bytes
from_bytes.doc:
Return the integer represented by the given array of bytes.

bytes
  Holds the array of bytes to convert.  The argument must either
  support the buffer protocol or be an iterable object producing bytes.
  Bytes and bytearray are examples of built-in objects that support the
  buffer protocol.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Indicates whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.

to_bytes.name: to_bytes
to_bytes.doc:
Return an array of bytes representing an integer.

length
  Length of bytes object to use.  An OverflowError is raised if the
  integer is not representable with the given number of bytes.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Determines whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.
  If signed is False and a negative integer is given, an OverflowError
  is raised.

GlobalMode.name: GlobalMode
GlobalMode.doc:
int([x]) -> integer
int(x, base=10) -> integer

Convert a number or string to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments
are given.  If x is a number, return x.__int__().  For floating point
numbers, this truncates towards zero.

If x is not a number or if base is given, then x must be a string,
bytes, or bytearray instance representing an integer literal in the
given base.  The literal can be preceded by '+' or '-' and be surrounded
by whitespace.  The base defaults to 10.  Valid bases are 0 and 2-36.
Base 0 means to interpret the base from the string as an integer literal.
>>> int('0b100', base=0)
4

bit_length.name: bit_length
bit_length.doc:
Number of bits necessary to represent self in binary.

>>> bin(37)
'0b100101'
>>> (37).bit_length()
6

conjugate.name: conjugate
conjugate.doc: Returns self, the complex conjugate of any int.

from_bytes.name: from_bytes
from_bytes.doc:
Return the integer represented by the given array of bytes.

bytes
  Holds the array of bytes to convert.  The argument must either
  support the buffer protocol or be an iterable object producing bytes.
  Bytes and bytearray are examples of built-in objects that support the
  buffer protocol.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Indicates whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.

to_bytes.name: to_bytes
to_bytes.doc:
Return an array of bytes representing an integer.

length
  Length of bytes object to use.  An OverflowError is raised if the
  integer is not representable with the given number of bytes.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Determines whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.
  If signed is False and a negative integer is given, an OverflowError
  is raised.

MapMode.name: MapMode
MapMode.doc:
int([x]) -> integer
int(x, base=10) -> integer

Convert a number or string to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments
are given.  If x is a number, return x.__int__().  For floating point
numbers, this truncates towards zero.

If x is not a number or if base is given, then x must be a string,
bytes, or bytearray instance representing an integer literal in the
given base.  The literal can be preceded by '+' or '-' and be surrounded
by whitespace.  The base defaults to 10.  Valid bases are 0 and 2-36.
Base 0 means to interpret the base from the string as an integer literal.
>>> int('0b100', base=0)
4

bit_length.name: bit_length
bit_length.doc:
Number of bits necessary to represent self in binary.

>>> bin(37)
'0b100101'
>>> (37).bit_length()
6

conjugate.name: conjugate
conjugate.doc: Returns self, the complex conjugate of any int.

from_bytes.name: from_bytes
from_bytes.doc:
Return the integer represented by the given array of bytes.

bytes
  Holds the array of bytes to convert.  The argument must either
  support the buffer protocol or be an iterable object producing bytes.
  Bytes and bytearray are examples of built-in objects that support the
  buffer protocol.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Indicates whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.

to_bytes.name: to_bytes
to_bytes.doc:
Return an array of bytes representing an integer.

length
  Length of bytes object to use.  An OverflowError is raised if the
  integer is not representable with the given number of bytes.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Determines whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.
  If signed is False and a negative integer is given, an OverflowError
  is raised.

can_show_chains.name: can_show_chains
can_show_chains.doc: return True, if this Rack contains a rack instrument device that is capable of showing its chains in session view.

chain_selector.name: chain_selector
chain_selector.doc: Const access to the chain selector parameter.

chains.name: chains
chains.doc: Return const access to the list of chains in this device. Throws an exception if can_have_chains is false.

drum_pads.name: drum_pads
drum_pads.doc: Return const access to the list of drum pads in this device. Throws an exception if can_have_drum_pads is false.

has_drum_pads.name: has_drum_pads
has_drum_pads.doc: Returns true if the device is a drum rack which has drum pads. Throws an exception if can_have_drum_pads is false.

has_macro_mappings.name: has_macro_mappings
has_macro_mappings.doc: Returns true if any of the rack's macros are mapped to a parameter.

is_showing_chains.name: is_showing_chains
is_showing_chains.doc: Returns True, if it is showing chains.

macros_mapped.name: macros_mapped
macros_mapped.doc: A list of booleans, one for each macro parameter, which is True iffthat macro is mapped to something

return_chains.name: return_chains
return_chains.doc: Return const access to the list of return chains in this device. Throws an exception if can_have_chains is false.

selected_variation_index.name: selected_variation_index
selected_variation_index.doc: Access to the index of the currently selected macro variation.Throws an exception if the index is out of range.

variation_count.name: variation_count
variation_count.doc: Access to the number of macro variations currently stored.

visible_drum_pads.name: visible_drum_pads
visible_drum_pads.doc: Return const access to the list of visible drum pads in this device. Throws an exception if can_have_drum_pads is false.

visible_macro_count.name: visible_macro_count
visible_macro_count.doc: Access to the number of macros that are currently visible.

SlicingBeatDivision.name: SlicingBeatDivision
SlicingBeatDivision.doc:
int([x]) -> integer
int(x, base=10) -> integer

Convert a number or string to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments
are given.  If x is a number, return x.__int__().  For floating point
numbers, this truncates towards zero.

If x is not a number or if base is given, then x must be a string,
bytes, or bytearray instance representing an integer literal in the
given base.  The literal can be preceded by '+' or '-' and be surrounded
by whitespace.  The base defaults to 10.  Valid bases are 0 and 2-36.
Base 0 means to interpret the base from the string as an integer literal.
>>> int('0b100', base=0)
4

bit_length.name: bit_length
bit_length.doc:
Number of bits necessary to represent self in binary.

>>> bin(37)
'0b100101'
>>> (37).bit_length()
6

conjugate.doc: Returns self, the complex conjugate of any int.

from_bytes.name: from_bytes
from_bytes.doc:
Return the integer represented by the given array of bytes.

bytes
  Holds the array of bytes to convert.  The argument must either
  support the buffer protocol or be an iterable object producing bytes.
  Bytes and bytearray are examples of built-in objects that support the
  buffer protocol.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Indicates whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.

to_bytes.name: to_bytes
to_bytes.doc:
Return an array of bytes representing an integer.

length
  Length of bytes object to use.  An OverflowError is raised if the
  integer is not representable with the given number of bytes.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Determines whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.
  If signed is False and a negative integer is given, an OverflowError
  is raised.

tempo.name: tempo
tempo.doc:
Get/Set the tempo value of the scene.
The song will use the scene's tempo as soon as the scene is fired.
Returns -1 if the scene has no tempo property.

tempo_enabled.name: tempo_enabled
tempo_enabled.doc:
Get/Set the active state of the scene tempo.
When disabled, the scene will use the song's tempo,and the tempo value returned will be -1Returns a bool indicating the state of the scene's tempo

time_signature_denominator.name: time_signature_denominator
time_signature_denominator.doc:
Get/Set the scene's time signature denominator.
The song will use the scene's time signature as soon as the scene is fired.
Returns -1 if the scene has no time signature property.

time_signature_enabled.name: time_signature_enabled

When disabled, the scene will use the song's time signature,and the time signature values returned will be -1Returns a bool indicating the state of the scene's time signature

time_signature_numerator.name: time_signature_numerator
time_signature_numerator.doc:
Get/Set the scene's time signature numerator.
The song will use the scene's time signature as soon as the scene is fired.
Returns -1 if the scene has no time signature property.

PlaybackMode.name: PlaybackMode
PlaybackMode.doc:
int([x]) -> integer
int(x, base=10) -> integer

Convert a number or string to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments
are given.  If x is a number, return x.__int__().  For floating point
numbers, this truncates towards zero.

If x is not a number or if base is given, then x must be a string,
bytes, or bytearray instance representing an integer literal in the
given base.  The literal can be preceded by '+' or '-' and be surrounded
by whitespace.  The base defaults to 10.  Valid bases are 0 and 2-36.
Base 0 means to interpret the base from the string as an integer literal.
>>> int('0b100', base=0)
4

bit_length.name: bit_length
bit_length.doc:
Number of bits necessary to represent self in binary.

>>> bin(37)
'0b100101'
>>> (37).bit_length()
6

conjugate.name: conjugate
conjugate.doc: Returns self, the complex conjugate of any int.

from_bytes.name: from_bytes
from_bytes.doc:
Return the integer represented by the given array of bytes.

bytes
  Holds the array of bytes to convert.  The argument must either
  support the buffer protocol or be an iterable object producing bytes.
  Bytes and bytearray are examples of built-in objects that support the
  buffer protocol.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Indicates whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.

to_bytes.name: to_bytes
to_bytes.doc:
Return an array of bytes representing an integer.

length
  Length of bytes object to use.  An OverflowError is raised if the
  integer is not representable with the given number of bytes.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Determines whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.
  If signed is False and a negative integer is given, an OverflowError
  is raised.

denominator.name: denominator
denominator.doc: the denominator of a rational number in lowest terms

imag.name: imag
imag.doc: the imaginary part of a complex number

numerator.name: numerator
numerator.doc: the numerator of a rational number in lowest terms

real.name: real
real.doc: the real part of a complex number

int([x]) -> integer
int(x, base=10) -> integer

Convert a number or string to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments
are given.  If x is a number, return x.__int__().  For floating point
numbers, this truncates towards zero.

If x is not a number or if base is given, then x must be a string,
bytes, or bytearray instance representing an integer literal in the
given base.  The literal can be preceded by '+' or '-' and be surrounded
by whitespace.  The base defaults to 10.  Valid bases are 0 and 2-36.
Base 0 means to interpret the base from the string as an integer literal.
>>> int('0b100', base=0)
4

from_bytes.name: from_bytes
from_bytes.doc:
Return the integer represented by the given array of bytes.

bytes
  Holds the array of bytes to convert.  The argument must either
  support the buffer protocol or be an iterable object producing bytes.
  Bytes and bytearray are examples of built-in objects that support the
  buffer protocol.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Indicates whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.

to_bytes.name: to_bytes
to_bytes.doc:
Return an array of bytes representing an integer.

length
  Length of bytes object to use.  An OverflowError is raised if the
  integer is not representable with the given number of bytes.

  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Determines whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.
  If signed is False and a negative integer is given, an OverflowError
  is raised.

capture_and_insert_scene( (Song)arg1 [, (int)CaptureMode=Song.CaptureMode.all]) -> None :

    the selected scene. Raises a runtime error if creating a new scene would exceed the limitations.

        void capture_and_insert_scene(TPyHandle<ASong> [,int=Song.CaptureMode.all])

capture_midi.name: capture_midi
capture_midi.doc:
capture_midi( (Song)arg1 [, (int)Destination=Song.CaptureDestination.auto]) -> None :
    Capture recently played MIDI material from audible tracks.
    If no Destination is given or Destination is set to CaptureDestination.auto, the captured material is inserted into the Session or Arrangement depending on which is visible.
    If Destination is set to CaptureDestination.session or CaptureDestination.arrangement, inserts the material into Session or Arrangement, respectively.
    Raises a limitation error when capturing into the Session and a new scene would have to be created but can't because it would exceed the limitations.

    C++ signature :
        void capture_midi(TPyHandle<ASong> [,int=Song.CaptureDestination.auto])

    Create a new audio track at the optional given index and return it.If the index is -1,
    the new track is added at the end. It will create a default audio track if possible.
    If the index is invalid or the new track would exceed the limitations, a limitation error is raised.If the index is missing, the track is created after the last selected item

    C++ signature :

MIDI recordings.

nudge_up.name: nudge_up

session record, but never starts playback.

and hits the global loop start region.

punch_out.doc:

and hits the global loop end region.

record_mode.doc: Get/Set the state of the global recording flag.

return_tracks.doc: Const access to the list of available Return Tracks.

root_note.doc: Set and access the root note (i.e. key) of the song used for control surfaces. The root note can be a number between 0 and 11, with 0 corresponding to C and 11 corresponding to B.

scale_intervals.doc: Reports the current scale's intervals as a list of integers, starting with the root note and representing the number of halfsteps (e.g. Major -> 0, 2, 4, 5, 7, 9, 11)

scale_name.doc:
Set and access the last used scale name for control surfaces. The default scale names that can be saved with a set and recalled are
'Major', 'Minor', 'Dorian', 'Mixolydian' ,'Lydian' ,'Phrygian' ,'Locrian', 
'Whole Tone', 'Half-whole Dim.', 'Whole-half Dim.', 'Minor Blues', 
'Minor Pentatonic', 'Major Pentatonic', 'Harmonic Minor', 'Harmonic Major', 
'Dorian #4', 'Phrygian Dominant', 'Melodic Minor', 'Lydian Augmented', 
'Lydian Dominant', 'Super Locrian', 'Bhairav', 'Hungarian Minor', 
'8-Tone Spanish', 'Hirajoshi', 'In-Sen', 'Iwato', 'Kumoi', 'Pelog Selisir', 
'Pelog Tembung', 'Messaien 3', 'Messaien 4', 'Messaien 5', 'Messaien 6', 
'Messaien 7'

session_automation_record.name: session_automation_record

swing_amount.doc: Get/Set access to the amount of swing that is applied when adding or quantizing notes to MIDI clips

tempo_follower_enabled.name: tempo_follower_enabled
tempo_follower_enabled.doc: Get/Set whether the Tempo Follower is controlling the tempo. The Tempo Follower Toggle must be made visible in the preferences for this property to be effective.

tracks.doc:
Const access to a list of all Player Tracks in the Live Song, exluding
the return and Master Track (see also Song.send_tracks and Song.master_track).
At least one MIDI or Audio Track is always available.

view.name: view

Representing the view aspects of a Live document:

Const access to a list of all visible Player Tracks in the Live Song, exluding
the return and Master Track (see also Song.send_tracks and Song.master_track).
At least one MIDI or Audio Track is always available.

TimeFormat.name: TimeFormat
TimeFormat.doc:
int([x]) -> integer
int(x, base=10) -> integer

Convert a number or string to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments
are given.  If x is a number, return x.__int__().  For floating point
numbers, this truncates towards zero.

If x is not a number or if base is given, then x must be a string,
bytes, or bytearray instance representing an integer literal in the
given base.  The literal can be preceded by '+' or '-' and be surrounded
by whitespace.  The base defaults to 10.  Valid bases are 0 and 2-36.
Base 0 means to interpret the base from the string as an integer literal.
>>> int('0b100', base=0)
4

bit_length.name: bit_length
bit_length.doc:
Number of bits necessary to represent self in binary.

>>> bin(37)
'0b100101'
>>> (37).bit_length()
6

conjugate.name: conjugate
conjugate.doc: Returns self, the complex conjugate of any int.

from_bytes.name: from_bytes
from_bytes.doc:
Return the integer represented by the given array of bytes.

bytes
  Holds the array of bytes to convert.  The argument must either
  support the buffer protocol or be an iterable object producing bytes.
  Bytes and bytearray are examples of built-in objects that support the
  buffer protocol.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Indicates whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.

to_bytes.name: to_bytes
to_bytes.doc:
Return an array of bytes representing an integer.

length
  Length of bytes object to use.  An OverflowError is raised if the
  integer is not representable with the given number of bytes.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Determines whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.
  If signed is False and a negative integer is given, an OverflowError
  is raised.

DeviceInsertMode.name: DeviceInsertMode
DeviceInsertMode.doc:
int([x]) -> integer
int(x, base=10) -> integer

Convert a number or string to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments
are given.  If x is a number, return x.__int__().  For floating point
numbers, this truncates towards zero.

If x is not a number or if base is given, then x must be a string,
bytes, or bytearray instance representing an integer literal in the
given base.  The literal can be preceded by '+' or '-' and be surrounded
by whitespace.  The base defaults to 10.  Valid bases are 0 and 2-36.
Base 0 means to interpret the base from the string as an integer literal.
>>> int('0b100', base=0)
4

bit_length.name: bit_length
bit_length.doc:
Number of bits necessary to represent self in binary.

>>> bin(37)
'0b100101'
>>> (37).bit_length()
6

conjugate.name: conjugate
conjugate.doc: Returns self, the complex conjugate of any int.

from_bytes.name: from_bytes
from_bytes.doc:
Return the integer represented by the given array of bytes.

bytes
  Holds the array of bytes to convert.  The argument must either
  support the buffer protocol or be an iterable object producing bytes.
  Bytes and bytearray are examples of built-in objects that support the
  buffer protocol.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Indicates whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.

to_bytes.name: to_bytes
to_bytes.doc:
Return an array of bytes representing an integer.

length
  Length of bytes object to use.  An OverflowError is raised if the
  integer is not representable with the given number of bytes.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Determines whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.
  If signed is False and a negative integer is given, an OverflowError
  is raised.

Track.name: Track
Track.doc:
This class represents a track in Live. It can be either an Audio 
track, a MIDI Track, a Return Track or the Master track. The Master 
Track and at least one Audio or MIDI track will be always present.
Return Tracks are optional.

    Returns true, if the given listener function or method is connected
    to the property "solo".

    C++ signature :
        bool solo_has_listener(TTrackPyHandle,boost::python::api::object)

stop_all_clips.name: stop_all_clips
stop_all_clips.doc:
stop_all_clips( (Track)arg1 [, (bool)Quantized=True]) -> None :
    Stop running and triggered clip and slots on this track.

    C++ signature :
        void stop_all_clips(TTrackPyHandle [,bool=True])

arm.name: arm
arm.doc: Arm the track for recording. Not available for Master- and Send Tracks.

arrangement_clips.name: arrangement_clips
arrangement_clips.doc: const access to the list of clips in arrangement viewThe list will be empty for the master, send and group tracks.

available_input_routing_channels.name: available_input_routing_channels
available_input_routing_channels.doc: Return a list of source channels for input routing.

available_input_routing_types.name: available_input_routing_types
available_input_routing_types.doc: Return a list of source types for input routing.

available_output_routing_channels.name: available_output_routing_channels
available_output_routing_channels.doc: Return a list of destination channels for output routing.

available_output_routing_types.name: available_output_routing_types
available_output_routing_types.doc: Return a list of destination types for output routing.

can_be_armed.name: can_be_armed
can_be_armed.doc:
return True, if this Track has a valid arm property. Not all tracks
can be armed (for example return Tracks or the Master Tracks).

can_be_frozen.name: can_be_frozen
can_be_frozen.doc: return True, if this Track can be frozen.

can_show_chains.name: can_show_chains
can_show_chains.doc: return True, if this Track contains a rack instrument device that is capable of showing its chains in session view.

canonical_parent.name: canonical_parent
canonical_parent.doc: Get the canonical parent of the track.

clip_slots.name: clip_slots
clip_slots.doc:
const access to the list of clipslots (see class AClipSlot) for this track.
The list will be empty for the master and sendtracks.

color.name: color
color.doc: Get/set access to the color of the Track (RGB).

color_index.name: color_index
color_index.doc: Get/Set access to the color index of the track. Can be None for no color.

current_input_routing.name: current_input_routing
current_input_routing.doc:
Get/Set the name of the current active input routing.
When setting a new routing, the new routing must be one of the available ones.

current_input_sub_routing.name: current_input_sub_routing
current_input_sub_routing.doc:
Get/Set the current active input sub routing.
When setting a new routing, the new routing must be one of the available ones.

current_monitoring_state.name: current_monitoring_state
current_monitoring_state.doc: Get/Set the track's current monitoring state.

current_output_routing.name: current_output_routing
current_output_routing.doc:
Get/Set the current active output routing.
When setting a new routing, the new routing must be one of the available ones.

current_output_sub_routing.name: current_output_sub_routing
current_output_sub_routing.doc:
Get/Set the current active output sub routing.
When setting a new routing, the new routing must be one of the available ones.

devices.name: devices
devices.doc:
Return const access to all available Devices that are present in the Tracks
Devicechain. This tuple will also include the 'mixer_device' that every Track
always has.

fired_slot_index.name: fired_slot_index
fired_slot_index.doc:
const access to the index of the fired (and thus blinking) clipslot in this track.
This index is -1 if no slot is fired and -2 if the track's stop button has been fired.

fold_state.name: fold_state
fold_state.doc: Get/Set whether the track is folded or not. Only available if is_foldable is True.

group_track.name: group_track
group_track.doc: return the group track if is_grouped.

has_audio_input.name: has_audio_input
has_audio_input.doc:
return True, if this Track can be feed with an Audio signal. This is
true for all Audio Tracks.

has_audio_output.name: has_audio_output
has_audio_output.doc:
return True, if this Track sends out an Audio signal. This is
true for all Audio Tracks, and MIDI tracks with an Instrument.

has_midi_input.name: has_midi_input
has_midi_input.doc:
return True, if this Track can be feed with an Audio signal. This is
true for all MIDI Tracks.

has_midi_output.name: has_midi_output
has_midi_output.doc:
return True, if this Track sends out MIDI events. This is
true for all MIDI Tracks with no Instruments.

implicit_arm.name: implicit_arm
implicit_arm.doc: Arm the track for recording. When The track is implicitly armed, it showsin a weaker color in the live GUI and is not saved in the set.

input_meter_left.name: input_meter_left
input_meter_left.doc: Momentary value of left input channel meter, 0.0 to 1.0. For Audio Tracks only.

input_meter_level.name: input_meter_level
input_meter_level.doc:
Return the MIDI or Audio meter value of the Tracks input, depending on the
type of the Track input. Meter values (MIDI or Audio) are always scaled
from 0.0 to 1.0.

input_meter_right.name: input_meter_right
input_meter_right.doc: Momentary value of right input channel meter, 0.0 to 1.0. For Audio Tracks only.

input_routing_channel.name: input_routing_channel
input_routing_channel.doc:
Get and set the current source channel for input routing.
Raises ValueError if the type isn't one of the current values in
available_input_routing_channels.

input_routing_type.name: input_routing_type
input_routing_type.doc:
Get and set the current source type for input routing.
Raises ValueError if the type isn't one of the current values in
available_input_routing_types.

input_routings.name: input_routings
input_routings.doc: Const access to the list of available input routings.

input_sub_routings.name: input_sub_routings
input_sub_routings.doc: Return a list of all available input sub routings.

is_foldable.name: is_foldable
is_foldable.doc: return True if the track can be (un)folded to hide/reveal contained tracks.

is_frozen.name: is_frozen
is_frozen.doc: return True if this Track is currently frozen. No changes should be applied to the track's devices or clips while it is frozen.

is_grouped.name: is_grouped
is_grouped.doc: return True if this Track is current part of a group track.

is_part_of_selection.name: is_part_of_selection
is_part_of_selection.doc: return False if the track is not selected.

is_showing_chains.name: is_showing_chains
is_showing_chains.doc: Get/Set whether a track with a rack device is showing its chains in session view.

is_visible.name: is_visible
is_visible.doc: return False if the track is hidden within a folded group track.

mixer_device.name: mixer_device
mixer_device.doc:
Return access to the special Device that every Track has: This Device contains
the Volume, Pan, Sendamounts, and Crossfade assignment parameters.

muted_via_solo.name: muted_via_solo
muted_via_solo.doc: Returns true if the track is muted because another track is soloed.

name.name: name
name.doc: Read/write access to the name of the Track, as visible in the track header.

output_meter_left.name: output_meter_left
output_meter_left.doc:
Momentary value of left output channel meter, 0.0 to 1.0.
For tracks with audio output only.

output_meter_level.name: output_meter_level
output_meter_level.doc:
Return the MIDI or Audio meter value of the Track output (behind the
mixer_device), depending on the type of the Track input, this can be a MIDI
or Audio meter. Meter values (MIDI or Audio) are always scaled from 0.0 to 1.0.

output_meter_right.name: output_meter_right
output_meter_right.doc:
Momentary value of right output channel meter, 0.0 to 1.0.
For tracks with audio output only.

output_routing_channel.name: output_routing_channel
output_routing_channel.doc:
Get and set the current destination channel for output routing.
Raises ValueError if the channel isn't one of the current values in
available_output_routing_channels.

output_routing_type.name: output_routing_type
output_routing_type.doc:
Get and set the current destination type for output routing.
Raises ValueError if the type isn't one of the current values in
available_output_routing_types.

output_routings.name: output_routings
output_routings.doc: Const access to the list of all available output routings.

output_sub_routings.name: output_sub_routings
output_sub_routings.doc: Return a list of all available output sub routings.

performance_impact.name: performance_impact
performance_impact.doc: Reports the performance impact of this track.

playing_slot_index.name: playing_slot_index
playing_slot_index.doc:
const access to the index of the currently playing clip in the track.
Will be -1 when no clip is playing.

solo.name: solo
solo.doc:
Get/Set the solo status of the track. Note that this will not disable the
solo state of any other track. If you want exclusive solo, you have to 
disable the solo state of the other Tracks manually.

view.name: view
view.doc: Representing the view aspects of a Track.

EffectMode.name: EffectMode
EffectMode.doc:
int([x]) -> integer
int(x, base=10) -> integer

Convert a number or string to an integer, or return 0 if no arguments
are given.  If x is a number, return x.__int__().  For floating point
numbers, this truncates towards zero.

If x is not a number or if base is given, then x must be a string,
bytes, or bytearray instance representing an integer literal in the
given base.  The literal can be preceded by '+' or '-' and be surrounded
by whitespace.  The base defaults to 10.  Valid bases are 0 and 2-36.
Base 0 means to interpret the base from the string as an integer literal.
>>> int('0b100', base=0)
4

bit_length.name: bit_length
bit_length.doc:
Number of bits necessary to represent self in binary.

>>> bin(37)
'0b100101'
>>> (37).bit_length()
6

conjugate.name: conjugate
conjugate.doc: Returns self, the complex conjugate of any int.

from_bytes.name: from_bytes
from_bytes.doc:
Return the integer represented by the given array of bytes.

bytes
  Holds the array of bytes to convert.  The argument must either
  support the buffer protocol or be an iterable object producing bytes.
  Bytes and bytearray are examples of built-in objects that support the
  buffer protocol.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Indicates whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.

to_bytes.name: to_bytes
to_bytes.doc:
Return an array of bytes representing an integer.

length
  Length of bytes object to use.  An OverflowError is raised if the
  integer is not representable with the given number of bytes.
byteorder
  The byte order used to represent the integer.  If byteorder is 'big',
  the most significant byte is at the beginning of the byte array.  If
  byteorder is 'little', the most significant byte is at the end of the
  byte array.  To request the native byte order of the host system, use
  `sys.byteorder' as the byte order value.
signed
  Determines whether two's complement is used to represent the integer.
  If signed is False and a negative integer is given, an OverflowError
  is raised.
